# Topic 3: CSS Basics — Styling the Web (Roadmap Checklist)

## Level 1 — Beginner: What CSS actually is and why it exists

- [ ] **Understand the problem CSS solves.** HTML's job is to describe *structure and meaning* (this is a heading, this is a list) — it deliberately says almost nothing about *appearance* (color, spacing, fonts, layout). Without any CSS at all, a browser renders a page using bare minimal defaults: black text, blue underlined links, basic spacing. CSS is the separate layer whose entire job is to answer "how should this structure actually look," keeping that concern cleanly apart from "what does this content mean."
- [ ] **Learn the anatomy of a CSS rule.** A rule is a *selector* (which elements this applies to) followed by a block of *declarations* in curly braces, where each declaration is a `property: value;` pair — e.g. `p { color: blue; font-size: 16px; }` means "every paragraph: make the text blue, 16 pixels."
- [ ] **Learn the three ways to apply CSS, and which is actually preferred:** inline (a `style` attribute directly on one element), internal (a `<style>` block inside `<head>`), and external (a separate `.css` file linked via `<link>`). External is the standard approach in real projects because it separates concerns cleanly, lets the browser cache the stylesheet across page loads, and lets one file style an entire multi-page site instead of repeating rules everywhere.
- [ ] **Learn the box model, because every single element obeys it.** No matter how an element looks, the layout engine treats it as a rectangle built from four layers, from the inside out: **content** (the actual text/image), **padding** (space between content and the border, inside the element), **border** (a visible or invisible line around the padding), and **margin** (space outside the border, separating this element from its neighbors).
- [ ] **Learn the basic selector types:** the type/element selector (`p` targets every `<p>`), the class selector (`.highlight` targets every element with `class="highlight"`), the ID selector (`#header` targets the one element with `id="header"`), and the universal selector (`*` targets everything).
- [ ] **Learn the core text and color properties:** `color` (text color), `font-family` (typeface, almost always written as a fallback list like `"Helvetica", Arial, sans-serif` in case the first choice isn't available on a user's device), `font-size` (text size), and `line-height` (vertical spacing between lines of text, which affects readability far more than people expect when first learning it).
- [ ] **Hands-on:** style the same simple page three different ways — inline, internal, and external — and notice in DevTools how each one actually shows up differently in the "Styles" panel, which builds your intuition for where styles come from later when debugging real pages.

## Level 2 — Intermediate: The cascade, specificity, and inheritance

- [ ] **Understand specificity as the answer to "which rule wins when two rules conflict."** When multiple CSS rules target the same element with different values for the same property, the browser doesn't apply them all — it calculates a "weight" per selector and the highest-weighted rule wins. Roughly, in increasing order of weight: element/pseudo-element selectors are weakest, class/attribute/pseudo-class selectors are next, ID selectors are stronger still, and inline styles outweigh all of them. `!important` overrides specificity entirely and should be treated as an escape hatch, not a normal tool.
- [ ] **Understand source order as the tiebreaker.** When two rules have *equal* specificity, the one written later in the stylesheet (or loaded later) wins — this is why duplicate-looking rules sometimes behave unpredictably until you check which one is actually declared last.
- [ ] **Understand the cascade as the overall layered decision process this all sits inside** — specificity and source order are the two main mechanics by which the cascade resolves which declarations actually take effect, which is literally where "Cascading" in "Cascading Style Sheets" comes from.
- [ ] **Learn the combinators that target relationships, not just isolated elements:** a space (`div p`) means "any `p` nested anywhere inside a `div`," a `>` (`div > p`) means "only a direct child `p`," a `+` (`h1 + p`) means "the paragraph immediately after an h1," and `~` (`h1 ~ p`) means "any paragraph that's a later sibling of an h1." These exist because real layouts are trees, not flat lists of isolated elements.
- [ ] **Learn pseudo-classes vs. pseudo-elements as two different ideas.** Pseudo-classes (`:hover`, `:focus`, `:nth-child(2)`) target an element based on its *state* or *position*, without needing extra markup or classes. Pseudo-elements (`::before`, `::after`) let CSS generate extra content that doesn't exist in the actual HTML at all — genuinely new "virtual" elements created purely by styling.
- [ ] **Understand margin collapsing, because it's a classic beginner trap.** When two block elements stack vertically, their adjacent top/bottom margins don't add together — the *larger* of the two wins and the smaller one is effectively ignored. This is a deliberate, specified browser behavior (not a bug), and not knowing about it leads to a lot of confused "why isn't my spacing what I calculated" debugging.
- [ ] **Understand inheritance, and why some properties inherit while others deliberately don't.** Typography-related properties like `color` and `font-family` inherit down to child elements by default, because it makes sense for a whole section of text to share a typeface unless told otherwise. Box-model properties like `margin`, `padding`, and `border` never inherit, because if they did, every nested element would silently accumulate spacing from every ancestor — visually chaotic and effectively unusable.
- [ ] **Learn the major units and what each is actually relative to:** `px` (an absolute, fixed unit), `em` (relative to the *parent* element's font size, which compounds confusingly when nested), `rem` (relative to the *root* `<html>` element's font size, far more predictable, hence widely preferred), `%` (relative to the parent's corresponding dimension), and viewport units `vw`/`vh` (relative to the browser viewport's width/height).

## Level 3 — Expert: Specificity at scale, performance, and real-world architecture

- [ ] **Understand why `box-sizing: border-box` became the near-universal industry reset.** By default (`content-box`), setting `width: 200px` only sizes the *content* area — padding and border get added on top, so the element ends up wider than 200px, which constantly surprises people doing layout math. `border-box` makes `width`/`height` include padding and border, so the number you set is the actual rendered size — most real-world projects apply `* { box-sizing: border-box; }` near the top of their stylesheet specifically to make sizing intuitive.
- [ ] **Practice calculating specificity precisely, not just intuitively** — e.g. understand why `#nav .item` (one ID + one class) beats `nav ul li a` (four element selectors) even though the second rule "looks" more specific by length, and recognize that this exact kind of mismatch between visual complexity and actual specificity is what causes most real "why won't my CSS apply" bugs.
- [ ] **Recognize over-reliance on IDs and `!important` as an architectural anti-pattern, not just a style preference.** The deeper principle: specificity should ideally rise predictably as components nest more deeply, so a developer can reason about override order just by reading the selectors. IDs and `!important` break that predictability by creating specificity "spikes" that can only be defeated with equally hacky counter-spikes — this is exactly the problem naming conventions like BEM were invented to avoid, by keeping every selector at roughly flat, class-only specificity.
- [ ] **Connect the box model back to the rendering pipeline.** Changing layout-affecting properties (`width`, `margin`, `padding`, `top`/`left` on a positioned element) forces the browser to recompute layout for potentially the whole page — an expensive "reflow." Changing properties like `transform` or `opacity` can often be handled purely by the compositor, skipping layout and paint entirely — which is exactly why performance-sensitive animations are written using `transform`/`opacity` instead of animating `margin` or `width` directly.
- [ ] **Know that modern CSS gives you deliberate tools to manage specificity and cascade complexity at scale:** CSS custom properties (`--main-color: blue;`, read with `var(--main-color)`) let you centralize values instead of repeating them, and `@layer` lets you explicitly define cascade ordering between groups of rules (e.g., resets vs. components vs. overrides) independent of source order or selector specificity — purpose-built answers to the exact specificity-war problem above.
- [ ] **Know that logical properties exist** (`margin-inline`, `padding-block`, etc.) as direction-independent alternatives to `margin-left`/`margin-top` style properties, written to remain correct automatically in right-to-left languages or vertical writing modes — worth knowing exists even before you need it for an internationalized project.
- [ ] **Understand the performance implication of where and how CSS loads.** External stylesheets linked in `<head>` are render-blocking by default — the browser won't paint anything until it has the CSS needed to know how to paint it, which is a deliberate trade-off (better to wait briefly than flash unstyled content), but it means stylesheet size and loading strategy directly affect perceived page load speed.
- [ ] **Hands-on:** open DevTools' box model diagram (in the Computed/Layout panel) on a real element and match what you see to the four layers conceptually; deliberately write two conflicting rules with different specificity and predict which wins before checking; toggle `box-sizing` between `content-box` and `border-box` on the same element and watch the rendered width change; stack two `<div>`s with different vertical margins and confirm the collapsing behavior for yourself.

## Quick self-check before moving on

You should be able to explain, without looking anything up: why HTML and CSS are deliberately separate layers rather than one combined language, why `padding`/`margin` don't inherit while `color`/`font-family` do, how to calculate which of two conflicting selectors wins without guessing, and why animating `transform` is cheaper for the browser than animating `width` or `margin`.